Batting statistics:

I. Introduction: In this project, we aim to analyze various hitting and pitching stats for Major League Baseball (MLB), the league leaders for every year in particular. Our analysis of these hitting and pitching metrics will serve as answers to our questions of interest. We would like to know how the National League (NL) leaders in various metrics compare over time. Through our big-picture question, we anticipate that we will also gain answers to how the statistics for the league leaders compare via year intervals, what certain peaks and valleys exist in our data, how some average-based statistics truly reflect upon the statistic itself (i.e., if the pitcher with the highest strikeouts per nine innings necessarily was the pitcher with the most strikeouts), and if we can draw a relationship between hitting and pitching metrics, especially over time. We plan to spotlight various MLB players through our investigation and analysis, while also acknowledging the impact of new technology on the collection of statistics over time. The purpose of investigating these questions is to work with a long-existing and ever-growing dataset that is meaningful to players, team officials, statisticians, and fans. These statistics and metrics are meant to determine the proficiency of performance and a players value to his team, further underscoring the importance of understanding the data.

import requests
from bs4 import BeautifulSoup
import pandas as pd

url = "https://www.baseball-almanac.com/hitting/hihits4.shtml"

# Set a custom user agent
headers = {
    'User-Agent': 'Mozilla/5.0 (Windows NT 10.0; Win64; x64) AppleWebKit/537.36 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/58.0.3029.110 Safari/537.3'}

# Send a GET request to the URL with headers
response = requests.get(url, headers=headers)

# Check if the request was successful (status code 200)
if response.status_code == 200:
    # Parse the HTML content of the page
    soup = BeautifulSoup(response.content, 'html.parser')

    # Find the first table on the page
    table = soup.find('table')

    # Extract data from the table
    table_data = []
    header_found = False

    for row in table.find_all('tr'):
        columns = row.find_all(['th', 'td'])

        # Check if the first column contains a numeric value (indicating a year)
        if columns and columns[0].text.strip().isnumeric():
            year = columns[0].text.strip()

            # Skip rows for years 1876 to 1900
            if 1876 <= int(year) <= 1900:
                continue

        # Check if the row contains the repeated header
        if len(columns) > 2 and 'American League' in columns[1].text.strip() and 'RBI' in columns[2].text.strip():
            header_found = True
            continue  # Skip this row

        if header_found:
            header_found = False
            continue  # Skip the next row after the repeated header

        # Check the length of the columns list
        if len(columns) < 5:
            continue  # Skip this row

        year = columns[4].text.strip()
        player = columns[5].text.strip()
        team = columns[7].text.strip()
        hits = columns[6].text.strip()

        # Exclude the row where the year is 2023 and the player is "American League"
        if year == '2023' and player == 'American League':
            continue

        table_data.append([year, player, team, hits])

    # Create a DataFrame
    df = pd.DataFrame(table_data, columns=['Year', 'Player', 'Team', 'Hits'])
    
    df = df.drop([0, 124]).reset_index(drop=True)

    # Print the DataFrame without the extra 'RBIs' column
    print(df[['Year', 'Player', 'Team', 'Hits']])
else:
    print(f"Failed to retrieve the webpage. Status code: {response.status_code}")

ERA:

In [16]:
import requests
from bs4 import BeautifulSoup
import pandas as pd
import re

url = 'https://www.baseball-reference.com/leaders/earned_run_avg_leagues.shtml'

# Set display option to show integers instead of decimals
pd.set_option('display.float_format', '{:.0f}'.format)

# Send an HTTP request to the URL
response = requests.get(url)

# Check if the request was successful (status code 200)
if response.status_code == 200:
    # Parse the HTML content of the page
    soup = BeautifulSoup(response.text, 'html.parser')

    # Find all tables on the page
    tables = soup.find_all('table')

    # Look for the table that likely contains American League data
    for table in tables:
        # Check if the table has at least 3 columns (assuming it's the right table)
        if len(table.find_all('th')) >= 7:
            # Extract data from the table and create a list of dictionaries
            data = []
            for row in table.find_all('tr')[1:]:  # Skip the header row
                columns = row.find_all(['th', 'td'])
                team = columns[0].text.strip()
                player_name = columns[1].text.strip()
                ERA = columns[2].text.strip()

                # Extract the year using regular expression
                year_match = re.search(r'\b\d{4}\b', team)
                year = int(year_match.group()) if year_match else None

                data.append({'Year': year, 'Player/ Team': player_name, 'Lowest ERA': ERA})

            # Create a DataFrame from the list of dictionaries
            df = pd.DataFrame(data)

            # Filter out rows for non-American League teams and create a copy
            df_al = df[df['Year'] >= 1901].copy()

            # Sort the copied DataFrame based on the 'Year' column in ascending order
            df_al.sort_values(by='Year', inplace=True)

            # Reset the index to start from 0
            df_al.reset_index(drop=True, inplace=True)

            # Print the resulting DataFrame
            print(df_al)

            # Exit the loop once the desired table is found
            break
    else:
        print('American League section not found or structure has changed.')

else:
    print(f'Error: {response.status_code}')

import requests
from bs4 import BeautifulSoup
import pandas as pd
import re

url = 'https://www.baseball-reference.com/leaders/W_leagues.shtml'

# Set display option to show integers instead of decimals
pd.set_option('display.float_format', '{:.0f}'.format)

# Send an HTTP request to the URL
response = requests.get(url)

# Check if the request was successful (status code 200)
if response.status_code == 200:
    # Parse the HTML content of the page
    soup = BeautifulSoup(response.text, 'html.parser')

    # Find all tables on the page
    tables = soup.find_all('table')

    # Look for the table that likely contains American League data
    for table in tables:
        # Check if the table has at least 3 columns (assuming it's the right table)
        if len(table.find_all('th')) >= 7:
            # Extract data from the table and create a list of dictionaries
            data = []
            for row in table.find_all('tr')[1:]:  # Skip the header row
                columns = row.find_all(['th', 'td'])
                team = columns[0].text.strip()
                player_name = columns[1].text.strip()
                wins = columns[2].text.strip()

                # Extract the year using regular expression
                year_match = re.search(r'\b\d{4}\b', team)
                year = int(year_match.group()) if year_match else None

                data.append({'Year': year, 'Player/ Team': player_name, 'Most Wins': wins})

            # Create a DataFrame from the list of dictionaries
            df = pd.DataFrame(data)

            # Filter out rows for non-American League teams and create a copy
            df_al = df[df['Year'] >= 1901].copy()

            # Sort the copied DataFrame based on the 'Year' column in ascending order
            df_al.sort_values(by='Year', inplace=True)

            # Reset the index to start from 0
            df_al.reset_index(drop=True, inplace=True)

            # Print the resulting DataFrame
            print(df_al)

            # Exit the loop once the desired table is found
            break
    else:
        print('American League section not found or structure has changed.')

else:
    print(f'Error: {response.status_code}')

import re

url = 'https://www.baseball-reference.com/leaders/H_p_leagues.shtml'

# Set display option to show integers instead of decimals
pd.set_option('display.float_format', '{:.0f}'.format)

# Send an HTTP request to the URL
response = requests.get(url)

# Check if the request was successful (status code 200)
if response.status_code == 200:
    # Parse the HTML content of the page
    soup = BeautifulSoup(response.text, 'html.parser')

    # Find all tables on the page
    tables = soup.find_all('table')

    # Look for the table that likely contains American League data
    for table in tables:
        # Check if the table has at least 3 columns (assuming it's the right table)
        if len(table.find_all('th')) >= 7:
            # Extract data from the table and create a list of dictionaries
            data = []
            for row in table.find_all('tr')[1:]:  # Skip the header row
                columns = row.find_all(['th', 'td'])
                team = columns[0].text.strip()
                player_name = columns[1].text.strip()
                hits_allowed = columns[2].text.strip()

                # Extract the year using regular expression
                year_match = re.search(r'\b\d{4}\b', team)
                year = int(year_match.group()) if year_match else None

                data.append({'Year': year, 'Player/ Team': player_name, 'Most Hits Allowed': hits_allowed})

            # Create a DataFrame from the list of dictionaries
            df = pd.DataFrame(data)

            # Filter out rows for non-American League teams and create a copy
            df_al = df[df['Year'] >= 1901].copy()

            # Sort the copied DataFrame based on the 'Year' column in ascending order
            df_al.sort_values(by='Year', inplace=True)

            # Reset the index to start from 0
            df_al.reset_index(drop=True, inplace=True)

            # Print the resulting DataFrame
            print(df_al)

            # Exit the loop once the desired table is found
            break
    else:
        print('American League section not found or structure has changed.')

else:
    print(f'Error: {response.status_code}')

import requests
from bs4 import BeautifulSoup
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import numpy as np

url = "https://www.baseball-almanac.com/hitting/hihits4.shtml"

# Set a custom user agent
headers = {
    'User-Agent': 'Mozilla/5.0 (Windows NT 10.0; Win64; x64) AppleWebKit/537.36 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/58.0.3029.110 Safari/537.3'}

# Send a GET request to the URL with headers
response = requests.get(url, headers=headers)

# Check if the request was successful (status code 200)
if response.status_code == 200:
    # Parse the HTML content of the page
    soup = BeautifulSoup(response.content, 'html.parser')

    # Find the first table on the page
    table = soup.find('table')

    # Extract data from the table
    table_data = []
    header_found = False

    for row in table.find_all('tr'):
        columns = row.find_all(['th', 'td'])

        # Check if the first column contains a numeric value (indicating a year)
        if columns and columns[0].text.strip().isnumeric():
            year = columns[0].text.strip()

            # Skip rows for years 1876 to 1900
            if 1876 <= int(year) <= 1900:
                continue

        # Check if the row contains the repeated header
        if len(columns) > 2 and 'American League' in columns[1].text.strip() and 'RBI' in columns[2].text.strip():
            header_found = True
            continue  # Skip this row

        if header_found:
            header_found = False
            continue  # Skip the next row after the repeated header

        # Check the length of the columns list
        if len(columns) < 5:
            continue  # Skip this row

        year = columns[4].text.strip()
        player = columns[5].text.strip()
        team = columns[7].text.strip()
        hits = int(columns[6].text.strip()) if columns[6].text.strip().isdigit() else None

        # Exclude the row where the year is 2023 and the player is "American League"
        if year == '2023' and player == 'American League':
            continue

        table_data.append([year, player, team, hits])

    # Create a DataFrame
    df = pd.DataFrame(table_data, columns=['Year', 'Player', 'Team', 'Hits'])

 # Identify rows with non-numeric 'Year' values
    non_numeric_years = df[~df['Year'].str.isnumeric()]
    
    # Drop rows with non-numeric years
    df = df[df['Year'].str.isnumeric()]

    # Convert 'Year' to numeric values
    df['Year'] = pd.to_numeric(df['Year'])

    # Create bins for the y-axis (Hits) with 30-unit jumps
    bins = range(70, 331, 30)
    labels = [f"{start}-{start + 29}" for start in bins[:-1]]

    df['Hits Range'] = pd.cut(df['Hits'], bins=bins, labels=labels, right=False)

    # Jitter the points within each range
    df['Hits Jittered'] = df.groupby('Hits Range')['Hits'].transform(lambda x: x + np.random.uniform(-5, 5, len(x)))

    # Create a scatter plot with jittered points
    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
    plt.scatter(df['Year'], df['Hits Jittered'], alpha=0.5)
    plt.title('Scatter Plot of Hits Over the Years with Hits Ranges (70-300, 30-unit intervals)')
    plt.xlabel('Year')
    plt.ylabel('Hits')
    plt.grid(True)
    plt.show()

else:
    print(f"Failed to retrieve the webpage. Status code: {response.status_code}")

Analysis:

From this scatterplot, we can see that roughly, hits over the years and decades have been about the same, but there are years that stick out, some as outliers. We can identify a few years in between 1920 and 1930 that exist as the peaks of the data set. Starting from the 1900s and the 1910s, the hits leader declined by the end of the 1910s, then spiked to highs in the 1920s and 1930s then eventually steadied out to an even spread over the next decades. 1981 sticks out as a valley and a distinct outlier in which the hit leader had about 135 hits, and we also have 2020 as an outlier, but that was a COVID-19 shortened season in which only 60 games were played.

import requests
from bs4 import BeautifulSoup
import pandas as pd
import re
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

url = 'https://www.baseball-reference.com/leaders/H_p_leagues.shtml'

# Set display option to show integers instead of decimals
pd.set_option('display.float_format', '{:.0f}'.format)

# Send an HTTP request to the URL
response = requests.get(url)

# Check if the request was successful (status code 200)
if response.status_code == 200:
    # Parse the HTML content of the page
    soup = BeautifulSoup(response.text, 'html.parser')

    # Find all tables on the page
    tables = soup.find_all('table')

    # Look for the table that likely contains American League data
    for table in tables:
        # Check if the table has at least 3 columns (assuming it's the right table)
        if len(table.find_all('th')) >= 7:
            # Extract data from the table and create a list of dictionaries
            data = []
            for row in table.find_all('tr')[1:]:  # Skip the header row
                columns = row.find_all(['th', 'td'])
                team = columns[0].text.strip()
                player_name = columns[1].text.strip()
                hits_allowed = int(columns[2].text.strip()) if columns[2].text.strip().isdigit() else None

                # Extract the year using regular expression
                year_match = re.search(r'\b\d{4}\b', team)
                year = int(year_match.group()) if year_match else None

                data.append({'Year': year, 'Player/ Team': player_name, 'Most Hits Allowed': hits_allowed})

            # Create a DataFrame from the list of dictionaries
            df = pd.DataFrame(data)

            # Filter out rows for non-American League teams and create a copy
            df_al = df[df['Year'] >= 1901].copy()

            # Sort the copied DataFrame based on the 'Year' column in ascending order
            df_al.sort_values(by='Year', inplace=True)

            # Reset the index to start from 0
            df_al.reset_index(drop=True, inplace=True)

            # Create 10-year intervals
            df_al['Decade'] = (df_al['Year'] // 10) * 10

            # Group by decade and calculate the mean hits
            df_decade_mean = df_al.groupby('Decade')['Most Hits Allowed'].mean().reset_index()

            # Print the resulting DataFrame with means for each decade

            # Create a scatter plot
            plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
            plt.scatter(df_al['Year'], df_al['Most Hits Allowed'], alpha=0.5)
            plt.title('Scatter Plot of Hits Allowed Over the Years')
            plt.xlabel('Year')
            plt.ylabel('Hits Allowed')
            plt.grid(True)
            plt.show()

            # Exit the loop once the desired table is found
            break
    else:
        print('American League section not found or structure has changed.')

else:
    print(f'Error: {response.status_code}')

Analysis:

The scatter plot printed above represents the Most Hits Allowed over the years, where each point represents a different player. From the plot, there appears to be a negative correlation between the two variables, meaning that as the year increases, the number of hits allowed decreases. This could be the result of outside variables, such as changes in the rules of baseball or the increase in the skillsets of baseball players.

import requests
from bs4 import BeautifulSoup
import pandas as pd
import re
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

url = 'https://www.baseball-reference.com/leaders/H_p_leagues.shtml'

# Set display option to show integers instead of decimals
pd.set_option('display.float_format', '{:.0f}'.format)

# Send an HTTP request to the URL
response = requests.get(url)

# Check if the request was successful (status code 200)
if response.status_code == 200:
    # Parse the HTML content of the page
    soup = BeautifulSoup(response.text, 'html.parser')

    # Find all tables on the page
    tables = soup.find_all('table')

    # Look for the table that likely contains American League data
    for table in tables:
        # Check if the table has at least 3 columns (assuming it's the right table)
        if len(table.find_all('th')) >= 7:
            # Extract data from the table and create a list of dictionaries
            data = []
            for row in table.find_all('tr')[1:]:  # Skip the header row
                columns = row.find_all(['th', 'td'])
                team = columns[0].text.strip()
                player_name = columns[1].text.strip()
                hits_allowed = int(columns[2].text.strip()) if columns[2].text.strip().isdigit() else None

                # Extract the year using regular expression
                year_match = re.search(r'\b\d{4}\b', team)
                year = int(year_match.group()) if year_match else None

                data.append({'Year': year, 'Player/ Team': player_name, 'Most Hits Allowed': hits_allowed})

            # Create a DataFrame from the list of dictionaries
            df = pd.DataFrame(data)

            # Filter out rows for non-American League teams and create a copy
            df_al = df[df['Year'] >= 1901].copy()

            # Sort the copied DataFrame based on the 'Year' column in ascending order
            df_al.sort_values(by='Year', inplace=True)

            # Reset the index to start from 0
            df_al.reset_index(drop=True, inplace=True)

            # Create 10-year intervals
            df_al['Decade'] = (df_al['Year'] // 10) * 10

            # Group by decade and calculate the mean hits
            df_decade_mean = df_al.groupby('Decade')['Most Hits Allowed'].mean().reset_index()

            # Plotting the line graph
            plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
            plt.plot(df_decade_mean['Decade'], df_decade_mean['Most Hits Allowed'], marker='o', linestyle='-')
            plt.title('Mean Hits Allowed per Decade (American League)')
            plt.xlabel('Decade')
            plt.ylabel('Mean Hits Allowed')
            plt.grid(True)
            plt.show()

            # Exit the loop once the desired table is found
            break
    else:
        print('American League section not found or structure has changed.')

else:
    print(f'Error: {response.status_code}')

Analysis:

This graph puts the data from the mean hits allowed table into a line graph. In this graph, we can see the mean hits allowed according to the various decades. This reinforces the relatively negative correlation throughout the years.

Hits Allowed Visualizations Summary: When looking at the hits allowed visuals, it was very interesting to see how it contradicted the findings in the previous section. Through our findings in the various graphs and tables for hits allowed, we saw that in the scatterplot and line graph, there was an obvious negative trend. import requests
from bs4 import BeautifulSoup
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

url = "https://www.baseball-almanac.com/hitting/hiwalk4.shtml"

# Set a custom user agent
headers = {
    'User-Agent': 'Mozilla/5.0 (Windows NT 10.0; Win64; x64) AppleWebKit/537.36 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/58.0.3029.110 Safari/537.3'}

# Send a GET request to the URL with headers
response = requests.get(url, headers=headers)

# Check if the request was successful (status code 200)
if response.status_code == 200:
    # Parse the HTML content of the page
    soup = BeautifulSoup(response.content, 'html.parser')

    # Find the first table on the page
    table = soup.find('table')

    # Extract data from the table
    table_data = []
    header_found = False

    for row in table.find_all('tr'):
        columns = row.find_all(['th', 'td'])

        # Check if the first column contains a numeric value (indicating a year)
        if columns and columns[0].text.strip().isnumeric():
            year = columns[0].text.strip()

            if 1876 <= int(year) <= 1900:
                continue  # Skip this row

        # Check if the row contains the repeated header
        if len(columns) > 2 and 'American League' in columns[1].text.strip() and 'RBI' in columns[2].text.strip():
            header_found = True
            continue  # Skip this row

        if header_found:
            header_found = False
            continue  # Skip the next row after the repeated header

        # Check the length of the columns list
        if len(columns) < 5:
            continue  # Skip this row

        player = columns[5].text.strip()
        team = columns[7].text.strip()
        hitter_walks = int(columns[6].text.strip()) if columns[6].text.strip().isdigit() else None
        
        # Exclude the row where the year is 2023 and the player is "American League"
        if year == '2023' and player == 'American League':
            continue

        table_data.append([year, player, team, hitter_walks])

    # Create a DataFrame
    df = pd.DataFrame(table_data, columns=['Year', 'Player', 'Team', 'Hitter Walks'])

    df = df.drop([0, 124]).reset_index(drop=True)

    # Convert 'Year' to numeric values
    df['Year'] = pd.to_numeric(df['Year'])

    # Create a scatter plot
    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
    plt.scatter(df['Year'], df['Hitter Walks'], alpha=0.5)
    plt.title('Scatter Plot of Hitter Walks Over the Years')
    plt.xlabel('Year')
    plt.ylabel('Hitter Walks')
    plt.xticks(range(1901, 2024, 10))
    plt.yticks(range(45, 250, 15))
    plt.grid(True)
    plt.show()

else:
    print(f'Failed to retrieve the webpage. Status code: {response.status_code}')

Analysis:

This scatter plot represents hitter walks over the years, where each each point represents a different player. There appears to be a slight positive correlation between year and hitter walks. This means that as the year increases, the number of hitter walks also increases.

    # Rename the columns
    df_decades.columns = ['Decade', 'Mean Walks']

    # Create a horizontal boxplot using mean walks per decade
    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
    plt.boxplot(df_decades['Mean Walks'], vert=False)
    plt.title('Horizontal Boxplot of Mean Hitter Walks per Decade')
    plt.xlabel('Mean Hitter Walks')
    plt.show()

else:
    print(f"Failed to retrieve the webpage. Status code: {response.status_code}")

Analysis:

This boxplot highlights the one outlier in this right-skewed distribution at roughly 147 walks. We can also see that the mean of this distribution is about 112.

Walks Visualizations Summary: Through looking at the various graphs for batter walks per decade, each visual hinted at a slight positive trend. This means that as time goes, the league leader in batter walks also increases. This slight positive trend was first seen in the scatterplot with a few very large spikes in the early 2000s. This slight positive trend also continued by looking at the mean walks per decade along with the line graph for the means where a general positive trend can be seen. When looking at the histogram, it was perfectly symmetric, so not much could be concluded from that, but when analyzing the boxplot, we can see an obvious outlier along with the mean being on the right side which shows a slight positive relationship.

import requests
from bs4 import BeautifulSoup
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import re

url = 'https://www.baseball-reference.com/leaders/BB_p_leagues.shtml'

# Set display option to show integers instead of decimals
pd.set_option('display.float_format', '{:.0f}'.format)

# Send an HTTP request to the URL
response = requests.get(url)

# Check if the request was successful (status code 200)
if response.status_code == 200:
    # Parse the HTML content of the page
    soup = BeautifulSoup(response.text, 'html.parser')

    # Find all tables on the page
    tables = soup.find_all('table')

    # Look for the table that likely contains American League data
    for table in tables:
        # Check if the table has at least 3 columns (assuming it's the right table)
        if len(table.find_all('th')) >= 7:
            # Extract data from the table and create a list of dictionaries
            data = []
            for row in table.find_all('tr')[1:]:  # Skip the header row
                columns = row.find_all(['th', 'td'])
                team = columns[0].text.strip()
                player_name = columns[1].text.strip()
                walks_allowed = int(columns[2].text.strip()) if columns[2].text.strip().isdigit() else None

                # Extract the year using regular expression
                year_match = re.search(r'\b\d{4}\b', team)
                year = int(year_match.group()) if year_match else None

                data.append({'Year': year, 'Player/ Team': player_name, 'Most Walks Allowed': walks_allowed})

            # Create a DataFrame from the list of dictionaries
            df = pd.DataFrame(data)

            # Filter out rows for non-American League teams and create a copy
            df_al = df[df['Year'] >= 1901].copy()

            # Sort the copied DataFrame based on the 'Year' column in ascending order
            df_al.sort_values(by='Year', inplace=True)

            # Reset the index to start from 0
            df_al.reset_index(drop=True, inplace=True)

            # Create a scatter plot
            plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
            plt.scatter(df_al['Year'], df_al['Most Walks Allowed'], alpha=0.5)
            plt.title('Scatter Plot of Walks Allowed Over the Years')
            plt.xlabel('Year')
            plt.ylabel('Walks Allowed')
            plt.xticks(range(1900, 2025, 10))  # Set x-axis ticks to 10-year intervals
            plt.yticks(range(25, 225, 25))  # Set y-axis ticks to start at 25 and go up to 200 in 25-walk intervals
            plt.grid(True)
            plt.show()

            # Exit the loop once the desired table is found
            break
    else:
        print('American League section not found or structure has changed.')

else:
    print(f'Error: {response.status_code}')

Analysis:

From observing this scatterplot, we see that the walks allowed statistic has fluctuated steadily through the decades. We can identify peaks around 1911, 1955, and 1976, valleys at 1919, 1981, and 2022, and an outlier at 2020, the COVID-19 shortened season.

MERGED DATA

Intro:

In this section, we will merge the data sets of Losses and HR allowed, two pitching statistics that we plan to investigate and see if they are related. As allowing a home run in baseball is a negative thing and the worst possible type of hit to allow, it would make sense to us that allowing the most home runs could be correlated with having the most losses on record. After merging these data sets, we will look for trends and correlations by visualizing the data using graphs.

Code For Merging Most Losses and HR Allowed:

In [53]:
import requests
from bs4 import BeautifulSoup
import pandas as pd
import re

# Function to extract data from the specified URL and create a dataframe
def extract_data(url, column_names):
    response = requests.get(url)
    
    if response.status_code == 200:
        soup = BeautifulSoup(response.text, 'html.parser')
        tables = soup.find_all('table')

        for table in tables:
            if len(table.find_all('th')) >= len(column_names):
                data = []
                for row in table.find_all('tr')[1:]:
                    columns = row.find_all(['th', 'td'])
                    team = columns[0].text.strip()
                    player_name = columns[1].text.strip()
                    value = columns[2].text.strip()

                    year_match = re.search(r'\b\d{4}\b', team)
                    year = int(year_match.group()) if year_match else None

                    data.append({'Year': year, 'Player/ Team': player_name, column_names[2]: value})

                df = pd.DataFrame(data)
                df_filtered = df[df['Year'] >= 1901].copy()
                df_filtered.sort_values(by='Year', inplace=True)
                df_filtered.reset_index(drop=True, inplace=True)

                return df_filtered

        print('American League section not found or structure has changed.')
    else:
        print(f'Error: {response.status_code}')
        return None

# URLs and column names
url_losses = 'https://www.baseball-reference.com/leaders/L_leagues.shtml'
url_home_runs_allowed = 'https://www.baseball-reference.com/leaders/HR_p_leagues.shtml'
column_names_losses = ['Year', 'Player/ Team', 'Most Losses']
column_names_home_runs_allowed = ['Year', 'Player/ Team', 'Most HR Allowed']

# Extract data and create dataframes
df_losses = extract_data(url_losses, column_names_losses)
df_home_runs_allowed = extract_data(url_home_runs_allowed, column_names_home_runs_allowed)

# Merge dataframes
merged_df = pd.merge(df_losses, df_home_runs_allowed, on=['Year', 'Player/ Team'], how='outer')

# Remove rows with NaN entries
merged_df.dropna(inplace=True)

# Print the cleaned and merged dataframe
print(merged_df)

The main takeaway from these trends in this line graph is that the two are not necessarily correlated, because there are many other statistics pitching-wise in baseball that can affect pitcher wins and losses, even if allowing home runs is one of the more impactful statistics.

Conclusion for HR Allowed and Losses: Throughout looking at these various graphs and plots that compare players who led in Losses and Home Runs Allowed in the same season, it was very interesting to see the findings. One would think that if someone led the league in most losses, then they would also lead the league in most home runs allowed since home runs are a way of giving up a lot of runs. In our findings, we saw that this was not necessarily the case. First, after merging and cleaning the data frame, we saw that there were only a total of 7 times where a player led the league in both stats. That was the first hint that this case where leading in both stats isnt common, as 7 out of 123 years is not a lot. Next, when looking at the line graph and scatter plot, both showed no true patterns to support the claim that the two are related. When looking at the scatterplot specifically, we saw that the points were scattered around the whole entire plot with points being in 3 of the 4 corners which was an immediate hint there is no true relationship. Lastly, when looking at the box plot and histograms of the two, we saw that the spread for Home Runs allowed was significantly larger than that of the losses. We also saw that in the histogram, the losses only had frequencies in 2 of the 7 possible intervals compared to the home runs allowed which had a frequency in 6 of the 7. Overall, when comparing players who led in home runs allowed and losses in the same season, we saw that there was no true comparison to be made. In mostly all of the graphs, we saw that there was neither a positive nor negative correlation between the 2. Although the 2 may seem related to each other, through looking at the graphs and plots, we saw that there was no true relationship or comparison to be made between these 2 pitching metrics.

Intro:

This section of our report merges the data sets of the league leaders of extra-base hits (XBH) and doubles, as we wish to see how related the two are over the years by seeing which seasons the league leader in XBH was also the league leader in doubles. It is important to note that doubles is a component of XBH, as XBH is computed as doubles plus triples plus home runs.

# Import libraries
import requests
from bs4 import BeautifulSoup
import pandas as pd

# Function to scrape and process data from the given URL
def scrape_and_process_data(url, xbh_or_doubles):
    headers = {
        'User-Agent': 'Mozilla/5.0 (Windows NT 10.0; Win64; x64) AppleWebKit/537.36 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/58.0.3029.110 Safari/537.3'}
    response = requests.get(url, headers=headers)

    if response.status_code == 200:
        soup = BeautifulSoup(response.content, 'html.parser')
        table = soup.find('table')
        table_data = []
        year = None  # Initialize year variable outside of the loop

        for row in table.find_all('tr'):
            columns = row.find_all(['th', 'td'])

            if columns and columns[0].text.strip().isnumeric():
                year = columns[0].text.strip()
                if 1876 <= int(year) <= 1900:
                    continue

            if len(columns) < 5:
                continue

            player = columns[5].text.strip()

            # Check if the 'Team' column is present before accessing it
            team = columns[7].text.strip() if len(columns) > 7 else None

            if xbh_or_doubles == 'XBH':
                value = columns[6].text.strip()
            elif xbh_or_doubles == 'Doubles':
                value = columns[6].text.strip()

            table_data.append([year, player, team, value])

        df = pd.DataFrame(table_data, columns=['Year', 'Player', 'Team', xbh_or_doubles])
        df = df.drop([0, 124]).reset_index(drop=True)
        return df
    else:
        print(f"Failed to retrieve the webpage. Status code: {response.status_code}")
        return None

def scrape_and_process_data(url, xbh_or_doubles):
    headers = {
        'User-Agent': 'Mozilla/5.0 (Windows NT 10.0; Win64; x64) AppleWebKit/537.36 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/58.0.3029.110 Safari/537.3'}
    response = requests.get(url, headers=headers)

    if response.status_code == 200:
        soup = BeautifulSoup(response.content, 'html.parser')
        table = soup.find('table')
        table_data = []
        year = None  # Initialize year variable outside of the loop

        for row in table.find_all('tr'):
            columns = row.find_all(['th', 'td'])

            if columns and columns[0].text.strip().isnumeric():
                year = columns[0].text.strip()
                if 1876 <= int(year) <= 1900:
                    continue

            if len(columns) < 5:
                continue

            player = columns[5].text.strip()

            # Check if the 'Team' column is present before accessing it

            if xbh_or_doubles == 'XBH':
                value = columns[6].text.strip()
            elif xbh_or_doubles == 'Doubles':
                value = columns[6].text.strip()

        df = pd.DataFrame(table_data, columns=['Year', 'Player', 'Team', xbh_or_doubles])

        # Filter out rows where the value is not numeric
        df = df[df[xbh_or_doubles].str.isnumeric()]

        # Drop the first and last rows if they exist
        if not df.empty:
            if df.shape[0] > 0:
                df = df.drop(index=0, errors='ignore')  # Drop the first row if it exists
            if df.shape[0] > 123:
                df = df.drop(index=124, errors='ignore')  # Drop the last row if it exists
        df = df.reset_index(drop=True)
        return df
    else:
        print(f"Failed to retrieve the webpage. Status code: {response.status_code}")
        return None

import requests
from bs4 import BeautifulSoup
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Function to scrape and process data from the given URL
def scrape_and_process_data(url, xbh_or_doubles):
    headers = {
        'User-Agent': 'Mozilla/5.0 (Windows NT 10.0; Win64; x64) AppleWebKit/537.36 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/58.0.3029.110 Safari/537.3'}
    response = requests.get(url, headers=headers)

    if response.status_code == 200:
        soup = BeautifulSoup(response.content, 'html.parser')
        table = soup.find('table')
        table_data = []
        year = None  # Initialize year variable outside of the loop

        for row in table.find_all('tr'):
            columns = row.find_all(['th', 'td'])

            if columns and columns[0].text.strip().isnumeric():
                year = columns[0].text.strip()
                if 1876 <= int(year) <= 1900:
                    continue

            if len(columns) < 5:
                continue

            player = columns[5].text.strip()

            # Check if the 'Team' column is present before accessing it
            team = columns[7].text.strip() if len(columns) > 7 else None

            if xbh_or_doubles == 'XBH':
                value = columns[6].text.strip()
            elif xbh_or_doubles == 'Doubles':
                value = columns[6].text.strip()

            table_data.append([year, player, team, value])

        df = pd.DataFrame(table_data, columns=['Year', 'Player', 'Team', xbh_or_doubles])
        df = df.drop([0, 124]).reset_index(drop=True)
        return df
    else:
        print(f"Failed to retrieve the webpage. Status code: {response.status_code}")
        return None

Intro:

This section aims to investigate the merged data sets of the league leaders in WHIP (walks and hits per innings pitched) and ERA (earned run average), and see by visualizing this merged data set if the two statistics are related and how they may affect each other. It is important to note that for the statistics WHIP and ERA, the lower (or closer to 0) the statistic is, the better, so the league leaders would have the lowest in the league. Explanations for these statistics can be found in section II of the report.

# Function to extract data from the table and create a DataFrame
def extract_data(url, column_name):
    response = requests.get(url)

    if response.status_code == 200:
        soup = BeautifulSoup(response.text, 'html.parser')
        tables = soup.find_all('table')

        for table in tables:
            if len(table.find_all('th')) >= 7:
                data = []
                for row in table.find_all('tr')[1:]:
                    columns = row.find_all(['th', 'td'])
                    team = columns[0].text.strip()
                    player_name = columns[1].text.strip()
                    value = columns[2].text.strip()

                    year_match = re.search(r'\b\d{4}\b', team)
                    year = int(year_match.group()) if year_match else None

                    data.append({'Year': year, 'Player/ Team': player_name, column_name: value})

                df = pd.DataFrame(data)
                df_filtered = df[df['Year'] >= 1901].copy()
                df_filtered.sort_values(by='Year', inplace=True)
                df_filtered.reset_index(drop=True, inplace=True)

                return df_filtered

        print(f'{column_name} section not found or structure has changed.')
        return None

    else:
        print(f'Error: {response.status_code}')
        return None

import requests
from bs4 import BeautifulSoup
import pandas as pd
import re
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Function to extract data from the specified URL and create a dataframe
def extract_data(url, column_names):
    response = requests.get(url)
    
    if response.status_code == 200:
        soup = BeautifulSoup(response.text, 'html.parser')
        tables = soup.find_all('table')

        for table in tables:
            if len(table.find_all('th')) >= len(column_names):
                data = []
                for row in table.find_all('tr')[1:]:
                    columns = row.find_all(['th', 'td'])
                    team = columns[0].text.strip()
                    player_name = columns[1].text.strip()
                    value = float(columns[2].text.strip()) if columns[2].text.strip().replace('.', '').isdigit() else None

                    year_match = re.search(r'\b\d{4}\b', team)
                    year = int(year_match.group()) if year_match else None

                    data.append({'Year': year, 'Player/ Team': player_name, column_names[2]: value})

                df = pd.DataFrame(data)
                df_filtered = df[df['Year'] >= 1901].copy()
                df_filtered.sort_values(by='Year', inplace=True)
                df_filtered.reset_index(drop=True, inplace=True)

                return df_filtered

        print('American League section not found or structure has changed.')
    else:
        print(f'Error: {response.status_code}')
        return None

        for table in tables:
            if len(table.find_all('th')) >= 7:
                data = []
                for row in table.find_all('tr')[1:]:
                    columns = row.find_all(['th', 'td'])

df_era = extract_data(url_era, 'ERA')

    # Explicitly create a copy and convert 'ERA' and 'WHIP' columns to numeric
    merged_df_cleaned = merged_df_cleaned.copy()
    merged_df_cleaned['ERA'] = pd.to_numeric(merged_df_cleaned['ERA'])
    merged_df_cleaned['WHIP'] = pd.to_numeric(merged_df_cleaned['WHIP'])

    # Aggregate data by year (using median in this example, but you can use mean or any other metric)
    agg_df = merged_df_cleaned.groupby('Year').agg({'ERA': 'median', 'WHIP': 'median'}).reset_index()

    # Scatter plot
    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
    plt.scatter(agg_df['ERA'], agg_df['WHIP'], color='blue', alpha=0.5)
    plt.title('ERA vs WHIP Comparison Over Year Intervals')
    plt.xlabel('ERA')
    plt.ylabel('WHIP')

    # Annotate points with years
    for i, txt in enumerate(agg_df['Year']):
        plt.annotate(txt, (agg_df['ERA'].iloc[i], agg_df['WHIP'].iloc[i]))

    plt.show()
else:
    print("Data cleaning process failed.")

df_whip = extract_data(url_whip, 'WHIP')
df_era = extract_data(url_era, 'ERA')

    # Explicitly create a copy and convert 'ERA' and 'WHIP' columns to numeric
    merged_df_cleaned = merged_df_cleaned.copy()
    merged_df_cleaned['ERA'] = pd.to_numeric(merged_df_cleaned['ERA'])
    merged_df_cleaned['WHIP'] = pd.to_numeric(merged_df_cleaned['WHIP'])

    # Aggregate data by year (using median in this example, but you can use mean or any other metric)
    agg_df = merged_df_cleaned.groupby('Year').agg({'ERA': 'median', 'WHIP': 'median'}).reset_index()

Intro:

In this section, we will investigate the metrics of K/9 (strikeouts per nine innings) and WAR (wins above replacement). Explanations for these statistics can be found in section II of this report. Briefly, WAR is a measure of a players value in all facets of the game, but for this section, since we are comparing WAR to K/9, which is exclusively a pitching statistic, we want to see if the pitching league leaders in WAR have also led the league in K/9 in the same year, to get a feel of how valuable strikeouts are when assessing a pitchers overall value.

import requests
from bs4 import BeautifulSoup
import pandas as pd
import re

# Function to extract data from the table and create a DataFrame
def extract_data(url, column_name):
    response = requests.get(url)

    if response.status_code == 200:
        soup = BeautifulSoup(response.text, 'html.parser')
        tables = soup.find_all('table')

        for table in tables:
            if len(table.find_all('th')) >= 7:
                data = []
                for row in table.find_all('tr')[1:]:
                    columns = row.find_all(['th', 'td'])
                    team = columns[0].text.strip()
                    player_name = columns[1].text.strip()
                    value = columns[2].text.strip()

                    year_match = re.search(r'\b\d{4}\b', team)
                    year = int(year_match.group()) if year_match else None

                    data.append({'Year': year, 'Player/ Team': player_name, column_name: value})

                df = pd.DataFrame(data)
                df_filtered = df[df['Year'] >= 1901].copy()
                df_filtered.sort_values(by='Year', inplace=True)
                df_filtered.reset_index(drop=True, inplace=True)

                return df_filtered

        print(f'{column_name} section not found or structure has changed.')
        return None

    else:
        print(f'Error: {response.status_code}')
        return None

                    year_match = re.search(r'\b\d{4}\b', team)

This conclusion was further backed up by the plots and graphs as no relationship was seen throughout all of the plots.

Conclusion for League Leaders In 2 Stat Categories: Through the 4 tests that were conducted in this section, it was interesting to see which ones were related to each other and which ones werent. As talked about earlier, one would think that stats so closely tied together such as Losses and HR Allowed would be correlated with each other, but as seen, that was not the case. In this section, we purposefully wanted to choose stats that on paper seem related to each other, so we could see whether or not they are truly tied to each other. One would also think that even though baseball has been around for such a long time, the league leaders in any given season would hover around a certain value, but contrary to that claim, every stat had its own share of spikes and dips. It was interesting to see how the 2 comparisons that we concluded did have a relationship were XBH and doubles along with ERA and WHIP. This finding is interesting because as mentioned, doubles play a part in calculating XBH, so they should have a relationship, whereas ERA and WHIP look at completely different stats. This finding that stats using itself in calculations for other stats being related, was found false when testing the relationship between K/9 and WAR. Through testing the relations of the players who led in both K/9 and WAR, it was odd to see how little of a relationship was present when strikeouts play such a big role in measuring how good a pitcher is. Overall, throughout testing to see how the league leaders in two stats compared on a given year, the conclusion that was able to be made is that no matter what stats are chosen, there is no definitive answer to whether or not they will be related. As seen through the 4 tests above, no matter how closely related stats seem on paper, whether or not they will be related to each other depends on many other factors than just the eye test.
